======================================================================
WHICH GRAPHS WITH I(G,2)=21 CAN BE Ω(T)?
======================================================================

Maximum number of directed odd cycles at each n:
  n=3: max |odd cycles| = 1 (exhaustive over 8 tournaments)
  n=4: max |odd cycles| = 2 (exhaustive over 64 tournaments)
  n=5: max |odd cycles| = 6 (exhaustive over 1024 tournaments)
  n=6: max |odd cycles| = 14 (exhaustive over 32768 tournaments)
  n=7: max |odd cycles| ≥ 35 (sample of 2000)

For H=21 via I(G,2)=21, we need Ω(T) to have:
  - 4 vertices (K₃-poisoned case): blocked by THM-201/202
  - 6 vertices: need 6 odd cycles in T
  - 8 vertices: need 8 odd cycles in T
  - 10 vertices: need 10 odd cycles in T (disjoint!)

Since K₁₀ = 10 ISOLATED vertices = 10 pairwise DISJOINT odd cycles,
this requires 10 vertex-disjoint odd cycles, needing ≥ 30 tournament vertices!
But for H=21, we need very few HP. At n=30, H is astronomically large.
So K₁₀ as Ω(T) with H=21 is self-contradictory: too many vertices → too many HP.

REFINED ANALYSIS: Can K₁₀ (10 disjoint odd cycles) give H=21?

K₁₀ as Ω means: 10 vertex-disjoint odd cycles, each contributing
factor (1+2^k) where k = cycle length. For 3-cycles: factor = (1+2) = 3.
If all 10 are 3-cycles: I(K₁₀, 2) = (1+2)^0... wait, that's wrong.

Actually I(K₁₀, 2) = 1 + 10·2 = 21. The 10 vertices of K₁₀ are the
10 odd cycles, each being an INDEPENDENT SET of size 1.
I = 1 + 10x means: empty set contributes 1, each single cycle contributes x,
and NO pair is independent (all pairs are adjacent in K₁₀).

Wait — K₁₀ has ALL edges! So there are NO independent sets of size ≥ 2.
This means every pair of odd cycles shares a vertex.
So K₁₀ = 10 pairwise-INTERSECTING odd cycles, not disjoint!

CORRECTION: The graph G with I(G,2)=21 and I=1+10x is K₁₀ (COMPLETE graph).
Ω(T) = K₁₀ means 10 odd cycles, every pair sharing at least one vertex.
This is the CLIQUE case, not the independent case.

SUNFLOWER STRUCTURE: 10 pairwise-intersecting 3-cycles through vertex v
  Need C(m,2) ≥ 10 other vertices: m=5 suffices (C(5,2)=10)
  Total: 6 tournament vertices, 10 directed 3-cycles through vertex v
  Each triangle = {v, a_i, a_j} for distinct pairs (a_i, a_j) from 5 others

  Ω = K₁₀ found! n=6, H=25, I(K₁₀,2)=21
    H≠21, so OCF says I(Ω,2)=H=25≠21. Ω≠K₁₀ actually.
  Ω = K₁₀ found! n=6, H=25, I(K₁₀,2)=21
    H≠21, so OCF says I(Ω,2)=H=25≠21. Ω≠K₁₀ actually.
